<DocsLayout title="Webhooks">
  <h1>Webhooks</h1>
  <p>
    EncodeSwarmr can send real-time notifications to external services when events occur in the system. Webhooks support Discord, Microsoft Teams, and Slack with HMAC-SHA256 signature verification and automatic retry on delivery failure.
  </p>

  <h2>Supported Providers</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Provider</th><th>Format</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Discord</td><td>Discord webhook embeds</td><td>Rich embeds with colour-coded severity</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Microsoft Teams</td><td>Adaptive Cards</td><td>Fully formatted cards via Incoming Webhook connector</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Slack</td><td>Block Kit messages</td><td>Structured blocks with context and section elements</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Configuration</h2>
  <p>Add one or more webhook targets to your <code>controller.yaml</code>:</p>
  <pre><code>webhooks:
  - name: discord-alerts
    url: https://discord.com/api/webhooks/123456789/abcdefgh
    provider: discord
    secret: my-hmac-secret
    events:
      - job.completed
      - job.failed
      - job.cancelled
      - agent.disconnected

  - name: teams-ops
    url: https://outlook.office.com/webhook/xxx/IncomingWebhook/yyy/zzz
    provider: teams
    secret: teams-secret
    events:
      - job.failed
      - agent.stale

  - name: slack-ops
    url: https://hooks.slack.com/services/T000/B000/xxxxxxxxxxxx
    provider: slack
    secret: another-secret
    events:
      - job.failed
      - agent.disconnected
      - agent.stale</code></pre>

  <h2>Available Events</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Event</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>job.created</code></td><td>A new job has been submitted to the system</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>job.completed</code></td><td>A job finished successfully</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>job.failed</code></td><td>A job failed after all retries are exhausted</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>job.cancelled</code></td><td>A job was cancelled by a user or via the API</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>agent.connected</code></td><td>An agent connected (or reconnected) to the Controller</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>agent.disconnected</code></td><td>An agent lost connectivity to the Controller</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>agent.stale</code></td><td>An agent has not sent a heartbeat within the stale threshold</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>HMAC-SHA256 Signature Verification</h2>
  <p>
    Every webhook delivery includes an <code>X-EncodeSwarmr-Signature</code> header containing an HMAC-SHA256 signature of the raw request body, computed using the <code>secret</code> you configured. Verify this signature on the receiving end to ensure authenticity and reject forged payloads.
  </p>
  <pre><code># Header format:
# X-EncodeSwarmr-Signature: sha256=&lt;hex-encoded-hmac&gt;

# Python verification example:
import hmac, hashlib

def verify_signature(secret: str, body: bytes, header: str) -&gt; bool:
    expected = "sha256=" + hmac.new(
        secret.encode(), body, hashlib.sha256
    ).hexdigest()
    return hmac.compare_digest(expected, header)

# Node.js verification example:
const crypto = require('crypto');

function verifySignature(secret, body, header) &#123;
  const expected = 'sha256=' + crypto
    .createHmac('sha256', secret)
    .update(body)
    .digest('hex');
  return crypto.timingSafeEqual(
    Buffer.from(expected),
    Buffer.from(header)
  );
&#125;</code></pre>
  <p>
    Always use a constant-time comparison function (e.g. <code>hmac.compare_digest</code> in Python or <code>crypto.timingSafeEqual</code> in Node.js) to prevent timing attacks.
  </p>

  <h2>Retry Delivery</h2>
  <p>
    If a webhook endpoint returns a non-2xx HTTP response or times out, EncodeSwarmr retries delivery with exponential backoff:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>1st retry: 30 seconds after initial failure</li>
    <li>2nd retry: 2 minutes</li>
    <li>3rd retry: 10 minutes</li>
    <li>4th retry: 1 hour</li>
    <li>After 4 consecutive failures the delivery is marked as permanently failed and no further retries are attempted</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Delivery history and failure reasons are visible in the admin UI under <strong>Settings → Webhooks → Delivery Log</strong>.
  </p>

